1. SDLC (Software Development Life Cycle)

Definition: A step-by-step process used to develop software.

Phases:

1. Requirement Gathering

· Collect and understand the client's requirements.

· Prepare a document of all project requirements.

2. Planning

· Estimate project cost, time, resources, and risks.

· Create the project plan.

3. Design

· Design the software architecture, database, and user interface.

· Acts as a blueprint for development.

4. Development (Coding)

· Developers write the source code based on the design.

· Build all required features.

5. Testing

· Check the software for bugs and errors.

· Ensure it works correctly before release.

6. Deployment

· Release the software to users.

· Install it on the production server.

7. Maintenance

· Fix bugs, improve performance, and add new features after deployment.


2. Functional Specification Document (FSD)

Definition: A document that describes the functional requirements, features, and expected behavior of the software.

Purpose:

Guides developers and testers.


3. Unit Testing

Definition: Testing a single unit (method/function/class) of a program to ensure it works correctly.

Key Points:

Performed by developers.

Finds bugs early.

Example tool: JUnit (Java).


4. Software Environments (Servers)

Development (Dev)

Developers write and test code.

New features are created here.

Quality (QA/Test)

Testers check the application for bugs.

Ensures the software works correctly.

Production (Prod)

Live environment.

Used by real users.

Flow:

Dev → QA → Production

5. IT Team Roles

Business Analyst (BA): Collects customer requirements.

Project Manager (PM): Manages the project.

Product Manager: Decides product features and vision.

Developer: Writes code.

UI/UX Designer: Designs the user interface.

QA Tester: Tests the software.

Database Administrator (DBA): Manages databases.

DevOps Engineer: Handles deployment and servers.

System Administrator: Manages systems and networks.

Technical Support Engineer: Supports users after release.


6. Project Manager vs Product Manager

Project Manager

Manages the project.

Focuses on time, budget, and resources.

Ensures the project is completed successfully.

Product Manager

Manages the product.

Decides features and product direction.

Focuses on customer needs.


7. Waterfall Model

Definition: A linear software development model where each phase is completed before the next begins.

Flow: Requirement → Design → Development → Testing → Deployment → Maintenance

Advantages:

Simple

Easy to manage

Good for fixed requirements

Disadvantages:

Changes are difficult

Customer feedback comes late


8. Agile Model

Definition: A software development model where the project is developed in small iterations (sprints) with continuous feedback.

Process: Plan → Design → Develop → Test → Review → Repeat

Advantages:

Easy to make changes

Faster delivery

Continuous customer feedback

Disadvantages:

Requires frequent communication

Time and cost estimation can be challenging


9. Waterfall vs Agile

Waterfall Agile

Sequential process Iterative process

Fixed requirements Changing requirements

Testing at the end Continuous testing

Less customer

involvement High customer involvement

Changes are difficult Changes are easy.
